@node not27 "INTERVIEW WITH THE REAL OLOGRAM"

INTERVIEW WITH @{B}THE REAL OLOGRAM@{UB}
-------------------------------

@{B}The  Real Ologram@{UB} (@{B}TRA@{UB}) is a new game company which is supporting the @{B}Amiga@{UB} game
market. Its first title is a fighting arcade: @{B}Olofight@{UB}.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}* Tell us, when did you got the idea to make a company to develop @{B}Amiga @{UB}games? @{UI}

@{B}The  Real  Ologram@{UB}  is a team of two people: me (@{I}Fabrizio Stoduto, @{UI}20), who does
the  programming and the management; @{I}Gaetano Russo @{UI}(24), in charge for graphics,
music  and  some programming. We met each other nine years ago, that is since we
moved  to the place where we live now. We have been into computers since we were
kids  and  we had @{B}Atari@{UB}s, 8bit @{B}Commodore@{UB}s and eventually the @{B}Amiga@{UB} (@{B}500@{UB}, @{B}1200@{UB} up
to  our  @{B}1200@{UB}s  on  steroids). I started programming in @{B}BASIC@{UB} on the @{B}C64@{UB}, then I
switched  to  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB},  using  @{B}Amos@{UB}  and,  a  bit  later,  @{B}Assembly@{UB}. @{I}Gaetano @{UI}
experienced  programming the @{B}C=16@{UB}, the @{B}C=128@{UB} (@{B}basic@{UB}/@{B}assembly@{UB}) and then the @{B}Amiga@{UB}
(@{B}Amos@{UB}/@{B}assembly@{UB}).  He  also got into graphics and music (he studied music for ten
years). As you can see, our stories are similar.

Our  main  project, as you can imagine, is @{B}Olofight@{UB}, which is getting all of our
time  and  resources.  We  also  have a friend of us helping on minor system and
network programming, @{I}Rudi Chiarito. @{UI}The web site is his duty, too.

Here  we  are  with  our  first  project,  @{B}Olofight@{UB}.  We  hope  you are going to
appreciate it.

We've  been  working for two years on it, full time. It's a BIG project! We were
always  interested  in  programming  games and two years ago we decided to begin
this  adventure.  We chose yet another beat'em up because, in our opinion, those
already  on  the  market  didn't fully exploit the @{B}Amiga@{UB} hardware and we weren't
satisfied  with  them in general, so we thought it would have been great to show
others what @{B}Amiga@{UB} is able to do despite years of stagnation. We drew inspiration
from  what  we considered good in similar games (@{B}Street Fighter@{UB}, @{B}Shadow Fighter@{UB},
@{B}Body  Blows@{UB},  @{B}Mortal  Kombat@{UB},  etc.)  and  added  other features (like the 3000+
colours on screen and more....).
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}*  Though @{B}Olofight @{UB}is aim to @{B}AGA Amigas, @{UB}you are doing a patch for graphic cards
and a CD version, it's true? Will it support @{B}CyberGraphx, @{UB}@{B}Picasso96 @{UB}or both? @{UI}

A  patch  for  Gfx  board  (@{B}CyberGraphx@{UB}  and @{B}Picasso96@{UB}) will be out soon, CD-ROM
version is already out!
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}*  @{B}Olofight @{UB} use more than 3000 colors in screen, how did you manage to do that?
Do you used Ham8 mode or Copper? @{UI}

We take the Copper to the limit, but we exploit the other @{B}AGA@{UB} chips as well.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}* Which programming language have you used to code @{B}Olofight @{UB}? @{UI}

@{B}Assembler@{UB} of course! ;-)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}*  We  know you were in @{B}Computer98 @{UB}at Cologne (Germany). What do you think about
this event? @{UI}

It  was  our  first  time  there  and we enjoyed the time we spent promoting our
title.  We  wish  there  were  more shows like Cologne, with many @{B}Amiga@{UB} users to
meet.  It  feels like being with friends. It was a nice experience for us and we
hope things will be even better next year.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}* Are you planning to support @{B}PowerPC @{UB}boards in your games? @{UI}

We're  quite  optimistic about the future of @{B}Amiga@{UB}, our/your beloved machine. We
know it has potential to grow. And we really like the enthusiasm of @{B}Amiga@{UB} users!
@{B}PowerPC@{UB}  is  definitely  an  important  step towards the future. We only hope it
won't  be  adversely  affected  by  marketing,  as happened in the past with the
@{B}Amiga@{UB}s we know so well...
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}*  @{B}Olofight @{UB} is  back with the tradition of old games packed with a quality box,
good  manual and register card. Do you think your products have to achieve total
quality? @{UI}

We  aim  to  bring back the quality of past games, we think this first effort of
ours is on the right path. Of course we can do better than that.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}* What do you plan for future games? @{UI}

If  things turn out well, we have many ideas for new games that we would like to
do  (@{B}Amiga@{UB} only, of course). Were @{B}Olofight@{UB} to sell well, we could also port some
@{B}PC@{UB}  games  to  the  @{B}Amiga@{UB}.  We think the @{B}Amiga@{UB} would benefit from that. Original
products get a higher priority, though.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}* Do you think to start programming 3D arcades like everybody do now? @{UI}

We  have  many  projects  that  we will reveal in the near future. 3D beat'em up
games  are definitely interesting stuff and there's nothing like that yet on the
@{B}Amiga@{UB}... ;)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}* How and where can people buy your products now? @{UI}

The  products  can be buy from us and all @{B}Amiga@{UB} dealers. Now. Check our web page
at @{B}www.ologram.com@{UB}.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}*  Do you think new @{B}Warp3D @{UB}software from @{B}H&P @{UB}will make easier coder's to make 3d
games? @{UI}

Yes, it looks like a promising tool for game programmers.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}*  Now  to finish, what do you think about @{B}Amiga Inc's @{UB}election of @{B}QNX @{UB}as OS for
the future @{B}Amiga? @{UB}Is @{B}Amiga @{UB}in the good way?.@{UI}

@{B}QNX@{UB}  is just the kernel partner. It's a good choice, but it's still a small part
of  the  whole @{B}AmigaOS5@{UB}. Until @{B}AI@{UB} starts talking to developers about the future,
with  concrete information, things will keep on being far from great. The market
is  getting  smaller  and  smaller and @{B}AI@{UB}'s clumsy moves regarding @{B}OS3.5@{UB} and the
ultra-hyper-mega-cool  chip  haven't  helped  at all. Indeed, they confirmed the
doubts of many people. Right now things don't look that great, but we still hope
they will get better. Much better, that is :-)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{I}*  Well, that's all. Thank you very much for your time Fabrizio and feel free to
tell whatever you want to our readers. @{UI}

Thank you very much!
